==Awards and honours==
<!-- "Honours" is the correct spelling. This article is written in South African English - not American. -->
In August 2002 she was awarded the Western Cape Golden Cross. During the award ceremony Western Cape Premier [[Marthinus van Schalkwyk]] said she had gone "beyond gold and swam her way into the hearts of not only South Africans but the whole world".<ref>{{cite web|author=Independent Newspapers Online |url=http://www.iol.co.za/sport/natalie-du-toit-gets-gold-again-1.516523 |title=Natalie du Toit gets gold again - IOL Sport |publisher=IOL.co.za |date=2002-08-26 |accessdate=2012-10-05}}</ref>

Du Toit was voted 48th in the [[SABC3's Great South Africans|Top 100 Great South Africans]] in 2004 by the [[SABC|South African Broadcasting Corporation]]. She won the [[Whang Youn Dai Achievement Award]] in 2008.

In December 2009 she received the [[Order of Ikhamanga]] in Gold "for her exceptional achievements in swimming."<ref>{{cite web|author=Independent Newspapers Online |url=http://www.iol.co.za/index.php?set_id=1&click_id=13&art_id=nw20091202221846636C634040 |title=Makeba chosen for Order of Ikhamanga - Politics &#124; IOL News |publisher=IOL.co.za |date=2009-12-02 |accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref>

On 10 March 2010, she was awarded the [[Laureus World Sports Awards|Laureus World Sportsperson of the Year with a Disability]] for "breaking down the barriers between disabled and able-bodied sport".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.laureus.com/press_releases?article_id=1975 |title=Press releases |publisher=Laureus |date= |accessdate=2012-08-28}}</ref>

